From 5e4cf4e2519e5e594f195379d00868e39ca5f644 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ram <chan2006@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 05:27:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Add 1-click Azure Connect via MSAL multi-tenant admin consent
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Second cloud provider for Brownfield auto-discover, using
Microsoft's officially recommended pattern for daemon/unattended
access: multi-tenant Azure AD app + admin consent (MSAL) for
identity, plus a separately-assigned Reader RBAC role for actual
resource access — Azure architecturally separates authentication
(OAuth/consent) from authorization (RBAC), unlike AWS where the
CloudFormation stack handles both trust and permissions together.

- lib/azure-connect/msal.ts: buildAdminConsentUrl() and
  acquireManagementToken(), using @azure/msal-node's
  ConfidentialClientApplication.acquireTokenByClientCredential() —
  the Client Credentials flow, Microsoft's documented approach for
  app-only/daemon scenarios exactly like this one.
- lib/azure-connect/scanner.ts: discovery via direct ARM REST calls
  (VMs, storage accounts, SQL servers) using the acquired token.
  Same resource types/properties as archai-cli's Azure provider for
  consistent findings regardless of connection method. Untested
  against a real Azure tenant (same honest caveat as the CLI's
  Azure/GCP providers) — written against the documented ARM API
  surface, not yet live-verified.
- app/api/azure-connect/init: generates a CSRF state token and the
  admin-consent URL.
- app/api/azure-connect/callback: Azure redirects here directly
  after consent (GET, not a fetch call) — looks up the connection
  by state (the security boundary here, not a session check, so
  added to the public middleware allowlist), stores the tenant ID,
  and redirects back into /brownfield with query params so the
  same browser tab picks up where it left off. Deliberately avoids
  the AWS flow's new-tab pattern, since OAuth redirects naturally
  return to the same tab — sidesteps the whole class of stale-state
  bugs we hit debugging AWS Connect.
- app/api/azure-connect/verify: attempts a real ARM call (not just
  token acquisition) to confirm the Reader role was actually
  assigned, since admin consent alone doesn't grant it — mirrors
  AWS Connect's verifyRoleAssumable in spirit.
- app/api/azure-connect/scan: same Auditor -> Planner -> Engineer
  -> ADR pipeline as every other Brownfield entry point.
- components/brownfield/BrownfieldClient.tsx: new 'Connect Azure
  (1-click)' option. Reads azure_step/connection_id/message from
  the URL on mount (via queueMicrotask to satisfy the
  set-state-in-effect lint rule) to restore state after the OAuth
  redirect round-trip, then cleans the URL.
- package.json: added @azure/msal-node (verified real, current
  version against npm).

Needs before this works in production:
1. Run create_azure_connections_table.sql in Supabase.
2. Register a multi-tenant Azure AD app (Entra ID -> App
   registrations -> multitenant), set redirect URI to
   {APP_URL}/api/azure-connect/callback, create a client secret.
3. Set ARCHAI_AZURE_CLIENT_ID, ARCHAI_AZURE_CLIENT_SECRET,
   ARCHAI_AZURE_TENANT_ID (NexPlan's own tenant ID) in Vercel.

Verified: tsc --noEmit clean, next build succeeds (4 new
azure-connect routes confirmed in route table), no new lint errors
beyond the one pre-existing no-html-link-for-pages issue (fixed one
real set-state-in-effect issue introduced by this change).
